<subSubSection pageNumber="797" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="797">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="797">Note:</emphasis>
Although Kellogg (in Howard, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="797">Fl. Lesser Antilles</emphasis>
4: 193. 1988) stated &quot;Type: Plumier&quot;, the precise element intended is unclear. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Linnaeus’">Linnaeus'</normalizedToken>
variety has 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Plumier’s">Plumier's</normalizedToken>
&quot;
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mill" authorityYear="1768" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Phytolaccaceae" genus="Rivina" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="scandens">Rivina scandens</taxonomicName>
racemosa, amplis solani foliis, baccis violaceis&quot; as its diagnosis, but the illustration (t. 39) accompanying this 1703 work is for the genus as a whole, including both this and &quot;
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Phytolaccaceae" genus="Rivina" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humilis">Rivina humilis</taxonomicName>
racemosa, baccis puniceis&quot;, so it cannot be assumed to depict only one of them, and cannot be regarded as original material for either. However, in the absence of original material for the name, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Greuter’s">Greuter's</normalizedToken>
treatment of the plate as the 
<typeStatus>lectotype</typeStatus>
is accepted as a neotypification.
</paragraph>
